sellerComment: I m selling my baby because of a baby.  While a trail-rated, six-speed, two-door, soft-top Jeep is awesome for dirt roads, snow, and summer drives with the top down, it is not great for child seats, infants, or wives who find it hard to shift and waive a rattle around.  So, the new kid is in, and my Wrangler is out.I bought this Jeep new in 2007.  I actually ordered it from the factory while I was deployed with the U.S. Army in 2006.  I had dreams of lifting it, slapping on some big, bad tires, and taking it off road.  As you can see from the photos, that never happened.  It s pretty much still stock, and it has rarely felt anything but pavement.  It has an after-market Pioneer stereo (iPhone hookup and Bluetooth) to go with the factory-upgraded Infinity speakers and subwoofer.  Clean CARFAX.I did your comparison shopping for you (but you should still do your own research), and here s what I found: Jeeps like this list around $12,900.  Those Jeeps have better wheels and newer tops.  They typically have higher miles, and they don t have the upgraded speakers.  Wear and tear is similar.  My Jeep has a golf ball size dent in the passenger door, and I ve worn out the steering wheel and floor.  Apparently, I ve put my hand and heel in the same spots everyday for the last ten years.  You can t Jeep Waive from anywhere else, though.  (If you re not going to Jeep Waive, don t call.)  There s a red one in Colorado Springs for $10,500 with 116,000 miles and a hard top.  There might be something wrong with it, but if there isn t, that s a great deal, and you should go buy that one!  If you miss it, though, give me a call.If you re curious, I now have a Volvo.

sellerComment: Say hello to my Jeep Wrangler arctic edition. If you have a real need for all-season capability, 4-Doors, or simply a strong desire to depart the beaten path, my 2012 Jeep Wrangler is a tough recipe to beat. I've maintained her well and only put 52K miles on her in 6 years, she's basically a new car, never had an accident and never broken down. Under the hood sits a powerful 3.6 liter V6 that produces 285 horsepower and almost as much torque. Combined with the rock-solid Dana front and rear axles, this 5-Speed automatic transmission will allow you to maintain civility or allow you to carve your own path where ever you see fit thanks to the locking differentials, Rock-Trac HD transfer case, and gas charged. This jeep goes beyond basic by offering Air Conditioning, 4 wheel drive, power windows/locks, and special badging. With city streets and freeways providing an increasingly unfriendly atmosphere to standard, car-based suspension and real ground clearance are increasingly handy for the committed urbanite. If you get the urge to take an open-air cruise, just remove the top, put on some shades, crank up the Infinity sound system, and hit the road! A strong safety cage surrounds you, multi stage airbags protect you, and Hill-start and stability control help you along the way. My arctic offers all of the legendary rock-climbing ability of America's favorite off-roader, with a dose of comfort to go along for the ride!-This is $3K below market value-She's been meticulously detailed-No off roading, ever -Inspected and given a full fluid refresh and certification by dealership of perfect mechanical conditionWhy I am selling her: I moved to Seattle from Texas in 2014 and rarely ever drive her, hence why she has 52K miles in just 6 years. carFeaturesText: NA
sellerComment: For Sale is an Extremely Clean, Original, 2- Owner Garage Queen, my 1985 Jeep Laredo CJ7. If you re looking up CJ7s I ll assume your aware of most of the features and all the Jeep has to offer. I can t honestly say this is one of the Cleanest CJ7s on the market right now. Jeep is a 5 speed manual. I bought the Jeep from the original owner 4- years ago (Shipped from Cali to NJ). I have a copy of the original title to prove this. As you re aware the Laredo was the Top of the Line CJ7 they offered and this one comes with Factory Air, Hard Top and Doors, Soft Top and Doors, and I think a Bikini top (I ll have to check). From my understanding the Jeep is ALL Original and EVERYTHING works as it did in 1985 (yes, the Clock still works too). I did have the Jeep re-painted and put on new decals and new Stainless Steel on the Exterior. The interior appears to have the Original Carpet! There is ZERO Rust on the Jeep (big reason why I bought a Jeep sight unseen from California). I put in $3500 worth of tune ups and repairs to whatever was needed the first month I had it   the Jeep now has a Brand-New Set of 31  BF Goodrich tires (with less than 200 miles on them). Why am I selling? Well I put on 3,000 miles in the 4-years I had the Jeep  so I obviously don t drive it much at all and the Jeep just sits in my garage. I have twin 4-year old daughters   so a CJ7 is not ideal to throw them in the back seat! A CJ7 is one of the only cars where you can buy   drive for a few years   then sell it at same price you got it for!! This is my 3rd CJ7 and yes, I will miss this dearly!

sellerComment: "The Secret Life of 5.9's"OK girls, listen up. Wanna buy an outrageous factory stock "family" SUV, America's greatest muscle car ever built?This is your chance, and it will cost you $90,000 less than a brand new Jeep "Trackhawk", yet it sets similar performance and visual standards.The greatest muscle car ever built, you say? Yes, it's simple: What other muscle car has 4-wheel drive? When you step on this in snow, it wiggles a little and then rips straight-ahead. The 2-wheel drive muscle car is in the ditch if it ever gets to snow in the first place. Plus it has functional hood engine cooling grills. The Great White Shark, is what it looks like. The 360 cu. in. Mopar engine is one of the most venerable engines ever put out in Detroit.Oh, and ya, speaking of Detroit city, the 5.9's were built at the Jefferson North Assembly Plant, Detroit, Michigan, thank you very much autoworkers of the USA.Anyhoo, you can see all this for yourself. Links aren't allowed here, but go to you tube and dial in on 5.9 Jeeps, hear them run with that stock performance exhaust, and see 'em go 125 miles per hour.Go to Hooniverse Obscure Muscle Car Garage and read up. Go to stevenhawkins and 4-wheeler and read up. Fastest production SUV in 1998, first high performance SUV, really, all the foreign sowing machines got in the game. This is a throaty V-8. Then go to "left-foot braking/Formula1" because that is the way you will want to drive the 5.9.By the way, MSRP in 1998, $38,175 which is $59,321 in 2017 dollars.

carFeaturesText: CD PlayerCruise Control
sellerComment: I have a very clean 2006 Jeep Wrangler LJ.  6 speed transmission, Black hard top with black spiderweb shade for the nice weather driving.  Silver in color with dark charcoal interior.  The Jeep just had a new oil pan gasket installed by the dealership I bought it from.  Also had new tires put on it 4,000 miles ago.  I installed new spark plugs within the last 1,000 miles as well and changed the transmission fluid with full synthetic.  Jeep also has a new battery and magnaflow exhaust.    Has large aftermarket LED lights up on the bumper.  I believe the fender flares are aftermarket (they are wider than normal) but other than that, the Jeep is stock.  Doors are full doors.  Jeep has the stock stereo, cruise control, and heat/AC work great.   I have never taken this Jeep off the pavement.The Jeep drives great!  It s a blast to drive.  Changes in the family and the purchase of a new pickup truck have forced the sale.  I will definitely miss it.  The bad - while clay barring and waxing the Jeep I found some rust in the front left fender where dirt and crud had embedded between the actual fender and the fender flare and created an issue.  I removed the fender flare, removed the rust (good sheet metal under the rust), and applied POR-15.  This spot was about the size of a quarter and was not through the metal.  This Jeep is not a  rust bucket  but I am trying to disclose everything.  On cold startup it has the  Jeep tick  that goes away as it warms up.  I asked online and was told this is fairly common and just part of owning a Jeep, but I am disclosing it as I am not a mechanic and when I asked, people told me it s just a Jeep thing.  When the motor is cold it has a tick noise, as it warms it goes away.  Again, from what I was told this is quite common.  This is a VERY CLEAN Jeep.  These Unlimited long wheelbase models are becoming more and more difficult to find, especially this clean.  Drives straight, unmolested, and clean!!!!

Front axle ultra-rare high-pinion version. Both have locking Electrac differentials. Axle ratios are 4.56:1 - which is a perfect match for 35" tires. Axles have only 8000 total miles on them.This Jeep is set up for serious off-road capability combined with good on-road driving manners. It has a well-tuned suspension, strong axles, proper gearing, front & rear lockers, high ground clearance, and tough underbody protection, yet you could drive it hours down the highway or every day to work without worries.One quirk however is that due to the design of lockers, the rear axle can occasionally bind, then release during tight turns on dry pavement .The bind makes the tires 'chirp' and the release makes a bang. This only happens occasionally and is due to the roller clutch design used for the locking function in these differentials. To confirm there's nothing actually wrong, I've had the differential examined by a certified tech and they found no issues and the wear patterns on the ring and pinions are fine.AVAILABLE EXTRAS: I have a ton of spare parts for this Jeep, locker parts, tow bar that attaches to custom bumper, spare suspensions parts, etc. I have a FULL SIZE 35" mounted spare tire.
